success.question_hint:
• 3k is 3 lots of k.
  • Three of the answers are the same as 3 lots of k.

success.question_text:
Which expression is equivalent to 9a – 3b – a + 4b?

Choose the correct option below.
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Simplifying

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

The symbol immediately before a term is the one belonging to that term. For example, in this question you must subtract 3b and subtract a, but add 4b.

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Index Notation
success.question_hint:
• As 2x3 is being squared you multiply by itself.
  • You need to work out 2x3 × 2x3.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When multiplying, if the base is the same, add the indices. When dividing, if the base is the same, subtract the indices. If a power is raised to a power, multiply the indices.

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Substitution
success.question_hint:
• You need to find the answer to 12 – 2(–3)2.
  • Work out (–3)2 before you multiply it by 2.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

The square of any number will be positive.

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Simplifying
success.question_hint:
• Work out how many x’s are in 2x2.
  • You can then add your answer to x.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Like terms have exactly the same pronumeral part. Only like terms can be added or subtracted.

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Equations and Inequalities
success.question_hint:
• Start by moving the 7 to the LHS and the b to the RHS.
  • Now swap the sides around.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Equations can be solved by adding the same number, or term, to both sides of the equation, subtracting the same number (or term) from both sides of the equation or by multiplying both sides of the equation or dividing both sides of the equation, by the same number or term.

success.question_text:
Which expression is equivalent to 3(2x – 1) + 2(5 – x)?

Choose the correct option below.
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Expanding
success.question_hint:
• Expand both pairs of grouping symbols.
  • You then need to collect like terms.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When expanding, every term inside the bracket must be multiplied by the term outside the bracket. After the brackets have been removed, collect like terms.

success.question_text: How many matchsticks will be needed if there are seven rows?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Patterns
success.question_hint:
• Consider how the triangles are in rows.
  • The first row has 3 matchsticks, the second row 6, the third row 9 and so on.

stimulus_1.text: A pattern of triangles is made with matchsticks:

stimulus_3.text: The number of matchsticks needed when there are different numbers of rows of triangles is shown in the table.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Use all the information given in a question: any tables, diagrams or written information may be useful.

success.question_text: Which is the solution to the equation 4x – 1 = 2 – x?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Equations and Inequalities
success.question_hint:
• The 1 and the x should both be swapped to the other side of the equals sign.
  • As they cross the equals sign you have 4x + x = 2 + 1 which you can solve.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

To find the correct solution to an equation in a multiple-choice question, substitute each of the options into the original equation to see which one satisfies it.

success.question_text: Which one of these points lies on the straight line joining (1, 3) to (12, 25)?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Coordinates and Graphs
success.question_hint:
• Look at x = 1, y = 3 and x = 12, y = 25.
  • Work out the rule linking y and x and check which option has the same rule.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Points that lie on the same straight line must all obey the same rule. This rule is called the equation of the line. For example, in this question the equation of the line is
y = 2x + 1.

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Factorising
success.question_hint:
• When you factorise, you need to move out the front of the grouping symbols the biggest possible common factor.
  • Both terms have 2 and x as factors.

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Tables of Values
success.question_hint:
• The only pair of numbers to be seen is x = 2, y = 5.
  • Substitute this pair into each of the four options.

stimulus_1.text: A table of values was drawn up to show values obeying a certain rule. The table was torn and only one of the y-values could be seen:

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

If a value substituted into an equation makes that equation true, you can say the value satisfies the equation.

success.question_text: Billy is 1.8 m tall and weighs 90 kg. Which statement is correct?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Problem Solving
success.question_hint:
• From the question, m = 90 and h = 1.8.
  • Substitute these values into the formula and work out what range his value of B fits into.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Read all the information carefully when solving a problem.

choice_4.label: There is not enough information to draw any conclusions about Billy's weight.

success.question_text:
Which is a solution to the equation 7x = 16 – 3(x + 8)?

Click the correct option below.
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Equations and Inequalities
success.question_hint:
• Expand the grouping symbols.
  • Collect like terms on the RHS and then move all pronumerals to the LHS.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Before attempting to solve an equation, first remove any brackets and collect like terms.

success.question_text: How many pins are needed to make 12 octagons?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Patterns
success.question_hint:
• Look at the number of pins and octagons to make up a rule.
  • The rule is pins = 6 × octagons + 2 and then substitute into this formula.

stimulus_1.text: A pattern of octagons has been made with pins and string:

review_4.column_1_text: If you have found a pattern in the differences between successive terms, you can use that pattern to find a particular value. For example, in this question you might have said that the number of pins is 2 more than 6 times the number of octagons. So, for 12 octagons, the number of pins would be 2 + 6 × 12 = 74.

success.question_text: What is the smallest possible value of n?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Equations and Inequalities
success.question_hint:
• Start with a guess and check.
  • Continue to increase your guess until it becomes ‘less than’.
